Remove the entire if block including the comment above it. The primary push path (plugins.state from US-002 and plugin.updated from US-003) now handles all updates.

The cleanest approach: pass setPlugins down to PluginCard (or a wrapper that handles toggle logic) instead of onRefresh.

In App.tsx:
- Keep loadPlugins for initial mount and plugins.changed fallback
- Pass setPlugins to PluginList instead of onRefresh

In PluginList.tsx:
- Replace onRefresh prop with setPlugins: React.Dispatch<React.SetStateAction<PluginState[]>>
- Pass it through to PluginCard

In PluginCard.tsx:
- Replace onRefresh prop with setPlugins
- handleToggleAll becomes:
  const handleToggleAll = (e: React.MouseEvent) => {
    e.stopPropagation();
    const newEnabled = !allEnabled;
    // Optimistic update
    setPlugins(prev => prev.map(p =>
      p.name === plugin.name
        ? { ...p, tools: p.tools.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: newEnabled })) }
        : p
    ));
    void setAllToolsEnabled(plugin.name, newEnabled).catch(() => {
      // Revert on failure
      setPlugins(prev => prev.map(p =>
        p.name === plugin.name
          ? { ...p, tools: p.tools.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: !newEnabled })) }
          : p
      ));
      showToggleError('Failed to toggle all tools');
    });
  };
- handleToggleTool becomes similar: optimistic flip, revert on error
- Remove .then(onRefresh) chains entirely

Note: The plugin prop to PluginCard is derived from the plugins state array in App.tsx, so when setPlugins updates, PluginCard re-renders with the new plugin data automatically. The plugin prop is just a snapshot — the setPlugins call updates the source of truth.
